ons-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>乌克兰罗博蒂恩附近——在夜色的掩护下，15 名乌克兰士兵沿着林木线爬到乌克兰东南部这个被俄罗斯占领的村庄的边缘，并在黎明后发动了袭击。</p><p>当乌克兰人开枪时，俄罗斯军队用机枪子弹还击。乌克兰无人机和大炮猛烈撞击俄罗斯阵地。经过一天的激烈战斗，造成两名乌克兰士兵死亡、多人受伤，该排设法在拥有约 150 所房屋的 Robotyne 定居点站稳脚跟。</p><p>乌克兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">两个月的反攻</a>又向前推进了一英里。</p><p> 6月初，乌克兰试图利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">西方训练和装备的</a>大型机械化编队冲破俄罗斯军队的防线，但面对纵深的雷区和俄罗斯空中力量，却陷入停滞。因此，乌克兰又转而采用了在 17 个月的战争初期为其取得成功的小部队战术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1262" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ad8ecb39-26bb-4a4d-b98b-c4700b367059-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>此类行动是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-military-kharkiv-russia-war-landmines-11672326884?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">斯卡拉特种部队</a>的专长，该部队约有 170 人，目前处于乌克兰战役的最前沿。这些士兵拥有不同的平民背景和军事经验，由尤里·哈卡维 (Yuriy Harkaviy) 少校领导，他身材魁梧，为他赢得了绰号“斯卡拉”(Skala)，即“岩石”，以演员“巨石”强森 (Dwayne Johnson) 的名字命名。</p><p>斯卡拉从奥里希夫附近的总部派出配备无人机的侦察队，以发现俄罗斯的阵地和装备，并呼叫炮火。他派出突击队，他们在进攻前沿着树林步行数英里。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》对斯卡拉的手下进行了一年的追踪，在此期间，该组织重新夺回了乌克兰东北部的部分地区，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-military-kharkiv-russia-war-landmines-11672326884?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">触发地雷</a>后造成人员伤亡，并在东部城市巴赫穆特屠杀了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-bakhmut-russia-soldiers-killed-11675810722?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来自瓦格纳集团的俄罗斯准军事战士</a>。</p><p>他们现在正在争夺南边路线上的一个小村庄罗布坦尼，以实现反攻的一个关键目标：到达亚速海，将俄罗斯占领军一分为二。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833128?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">斯卡拉的手下协调了战斗行动，以控制乌克兰的罗布坦村。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>斯卡拉的人于七月初抵达该地区。俄罗斯人花了几个月的时间在东南部准备防御线，其中包括数英里的深战壕和数千个地雷。他们击退了乌克兰最初试图用坦克和装甲运兵车以大纵队推进的企图。</p><p>乌克兰指挥官决定，要在被细细林木线隔开的平坦田野中前进，他们需要更好的侦察和步兵突击队来帮助清理道路。</p><p>斯卡拉搬进了罗布坦以北一栋被桑树环绕的废弃房屋。与他一起的许多人从战争第一天起就一直在战斗，几乎没有休息过。大多数是在工作中学到的。斯卡拉直言不讳的参谋长在培训中心挑选了新志愿者。</p><p>在对该地区发起攻击之前，斯卡拉的无人机小组日夜飞行，获取俄罗斯阵地的图片，并指挥炮手攻击它们。突击队长途跋涉以避免被发现，有时会携带苏联时代或缴获的俄罗斯步枪，这样他们就可以从他们杀死的俄罗斯人那里拾取弹药，而不是为西方制造的枪支携带额外的子弹。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833127?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰侦察队使用无人机发现俄罗斯部队和装备并呼叫炮火。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833131?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">斯卡拉的无人机小组昼夜飞行，拍摄俄罗斯阵地和指挥炮手的照片。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>斯卡拉行动室的墙上装饰着缴获的俄罗斯武器，那里的一排屏幕显示着无人机的画面，空调机组在夏季的炎热中苦苦挣扎。</p><p>上周，斯卡拉的手下将俄罗斯军队从战壕中驱逐出来，并摧毁了罗布坦以西一个混凝土掩体中的机枪巢穴。周二早些时候，乌克兰人从四个方向袭击了该村庄。从北面进攻的小队在战胜了第一所房子里的一名机枪手后，前进到了最远的地方，到达了村庄的墓地。</p><p>俄罗斯人用装甲车、手榴弹和迫击炮进行反击。夜幕降临，斯卡拉的部队需要增援。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833130?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">斯卡拉的部队在乌克兰东南部的战斗前集结。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833133?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 《华尔街日报》对斯卡拉的手下进行了一年的追踪。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>斯卡拉给附近的旅指挥官打电话。他们召集了志愿者：一个旅的几名志愿者，另一个旅的十几名志愿者，第三个旅的二十多名志愿者。</p><p>当斯卡拉在地图上勾画出各小队应如何进入村庄时，他的一名部下在村庄西边发现了一门俄罗斯 120 毫米迫击炮。斯卡拉通过电话将该位置告知另一名指挥官。五分钟后，军官回电：迫击炮已被摧毁。</p><p>阳台上，十几个新兵正在准备战斗。其中包括 41 岁的护士 Anatoliy Shkryabniy，自从十年前颈部被刺伤以来，他的右臂一直很虚弱。一个月前，他自愿入伍，并说他右手的手指可以扣动扳机。 “我为什么要等待导弹降落在我的公寓？”他说。</p><p>他旁边站着鲁斯兰·卢森科 (Ruslan Lutsenko)，他是一位 47 岁的农场工人，有四个孩子。 “我必须捍卫他们，”他说。</p><p>他们挤进一辆绿色面包车出发了。一些人会前往罗博坦，而另一些人则被保留。</p><p>与此同时，斯卡拉的手下正在紧急疏散伤员。</p><p>随身摄像机拍摄的救援工作视频显示，一名士兵从一辆美制<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allies-say-armored-vehicles-will-give-ukraines-troops-an-edge-11672958229?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">布拉德利战车</a>后部跳下，跑向一群人，其中包括两名受伤的人，他们躲在另一辆损坏的装甲车后面。</p><p> “F——，伙计们，让我们拖住他们吧，”士兵说。</p><p>两名受伤男子筋疲力尽，浑身是泥，仍躺在地上进行抵抗。 “别喊，”其中一人说道，其他人则试图给他加油。</p><p> “我们他妈的离开这里吧，”另一名士兵喊道。他们把呻吟着的人拖进布拉德利号的后部，然后关闭了坡道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833126?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尤里·哈卡维少校，绰号“巨石斯卡拉”，因其与演员“巨石”道恩·强森的相似而得名。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833124?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">斯卡拉的部队专门针对乌克兰境内的俄罗斯军队实施小部队战术。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>天色渐暗，另一名斯卡拉士兵骑着摩托车沿着农田边的小路出发。他多次前往疏散紧随其后的三名受伤人员。</p><p>夜幕降临，一支无人机小组出发前往距离罗博坦约 3 英里的一片田地，检查村庄北部是否有俄罗斯人的活动。</p><p>他们用防蚊喷雾覆盖自己——其中一人开玩笑说，“我们的主要敌人在这里”——并在从俄罗斯人手中夺取的战壕中占据阵地。</p><p>这名飞行员是一名 31 岁的焊工，名叫 Lyutsyk，是路西法 (Lucifer) 的缩写，这是他妻子开玩笑给他取的绰号。他派出了他的无人机，这是一架带有四个旋翼的四轴飞行器，飞向 Robotyne。当天空变暗时，他按下开关打开了飞船的热成像相机。他指出前线散落着俄罗斯炸弹和报废的乌克兰车辆造成的弹坑。一切都很安静。</p><p>回到总部，斯卡拉正在操作室里仔细研究地图。</p><p> “我们已经扭转了局势，”他说。 “最重要的是进入那里，俄罗斯人就会四散。”</p><p>第二天早上，斯卡拉报告了一次成功的行动：尽管遭受了损失，增援部队还是在罗布坦北部占据了更坚固的阵地。</p><p> “他们进去挖了挖，”他说。 “动机就是一切。”</p><p>写信给詹姆斯·马森<a href="mailto:james.marson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">james.marson@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833129?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">斯卡拉的手下正在执行无人机任务，检查乌克兰罗布泰尼的俄罗斯阵地。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833132?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">特种部队于七月初抵达罗布坦附近地区。</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tropics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-Russia-d9ef32a3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tropics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-Russia-d9ef32a3<author><![CDATA[James Marson]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>图片新闻</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Lifts Ban on Group Tours to U.S. and Other Countries]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>尽管地缘政治紧张局势挥之不去，北京还将允许团体旅行前往日本、韩国和澳大利亚<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124280"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833090?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">目前，中国游客可以组团前往全球近140个国家。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124280"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：郑诗琳 ( <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/selina-cheng" itemprop="url" rel="author">Selina Cheng)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 7:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-lifts-ban-on-group-tours-to-u-s-and-other-countries-in-boost-to-global-travel-industry-1b467c78"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——周四，中国取消了对前往美国、澳大利亚、韩国和日本的团体旅游的限制，此举将在三年的大流行限制之后提振全球旅游业。</p><p>周四，中国文化和旅游部在批准团体旅游的国家名单中新增近80个目的地，即日起生效。这些国家是目前旅行社带领的第三批跟团游可以去的国家，其中包括一些最受中国度假者欢迎的东亚国家。</p><p>随着周四的宣布，中国游客现在可以组团前往全球近 140 个国家。几十个国家仍被排除在外，包括加拿大、乌克兰以及南美洲和非洲的一些国家。在大流行期间，中国没有限制个人出国旅行，但获得适当的文件很困难，而且新冠病毒预防措施使返回中国变得繁重。</p><p>尽管去年全球旅行和旅游业基本恢复，但中国大陆仍然是一个主要的例外，直到北京去年 12 月开始取消大流行时期的边境限制。对于许多中国大陆人来说，尤其是那些不会说外语的人来说，旅游团让出国旅游变得更加容易。</p><p>在Covid-19大流行之前，中国已成为全球许多旅游目的地最大、最有价值的游客来源国。然后，三年来，这些国家的许多旅游业都在想什么时候才能再次允许中国的国际旅行，以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thailand-pins-hopes-on-return-of-long-missed-chinese-tourists-11675708696?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">需要多长时间才能恢复到大流行前的水平</a>。</p><p>例如，政府表示，日本 6 月份的游客人数恢复到 2019 年水平的 72%，而中国游客的数字仅为 24%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833089?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">据国际货币基金组织称，疫情爆发前，中国游客是全球最大的旅游消费群体。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tomohiro Ohsumi/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国游客数量可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/worlds-biggest-tourism-spenders-arent-travelingand-may-not-for-years-3195de39" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在一段时间内不会恢复到疫情前的水平（</a>如果有的话）。由于对经济的担忧，许多中国家庭的家庭财务状况变得紧张。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">航空公司尚未恢复全部航班</a>，而签证和护照积压仍然是一个问题。分析人士称，越来越多的中国人开始在国内度假，而不是出国度假。</p><p>即便如此，中国出境旅游的任何反弹除了经济影响外还可能产生无形影响。</p><p>专家表示，考虑到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">中国入境旅游业急剧下降</a>，自疫情爆发前以来，中国公民与外国人和其他国家互动的机会急剧减少，这是地缘政治紧张局势的一个因素。</p><p>国际货币基金组织的数据显示，疫情爆发前，中国游客是全球最大的旅游消费群体，2019年海外消费达2550亿美元。位居第二的美国游客花费的金额略多于这个数字的一​​半。</p><p>在澳大利亚，2019年中国游客在该国花费的14亿美元中，中国旅行团占了四分之一以上。6月，澳大利亚通过恢复在中国的全球广告活动，加大了吸引中国游客回来的力度。</p><p> BridgeClimb 的负责人黛布·齐默 (Deb Zimmer) 表示，中国游客的回归将代表悉尼旅游业复苏的“实质性飞跃”。BridgeClimb 提供悉尼海港大桥顶部的团体旅游服务。</p><p>两国之间的贸易和外交关系在疫情期间变得紧张，时任总理斯科特·莫里森呼吁对Covid-19的起源进行调查，这激怒了北京。Covid-19是在中国首次发现的。去年选出的澳大利亚新政府推动了两国关系的改善。澳大利亚贸易和旅游部长表示，中国旅游团的回归也将有助于稳定澳大利亚与中国的关系</p>唐·法雷尔.<p></p><p>在韩国，中国团体旅游复兴的希望尤其明显。在Covid-19之前的几年里，中国的团体游韩国已经陷入深度冻结，此前中国禁止其旅游团前往该国，这显然是对首尔决定安装北京强烈反对的美国导弹防御系统的报复。 。</p><p>周四，韩泰化妆品公司和旅行社<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/032350" class="">乐天旅游发展</a>公司（乐天旅游开发公司<span class="company-name-type">）</span>这两家预计将受益于中国旅游业增长的公司的股价均飙升了 30% 左右。国营赌场运营商 Grand Korean Leisure 股价上涨超过 20%。</p><p>根据韩国政府数据，2019年，中国游客每次访问该国的平均花费约为1,600美元，是日本游客的两倍多，比美国游客高出约三分之一</p><p>日本的零售和旅游股同样受到北京消息的提振。经营受游客欢迎的东京百货商店的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/3099" class="">三越伊势丹控股公司</a><span class="company-name-type">周四</span>上涨 4.6%，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/9201" class="company-name">日本航空则</a>上涨 4.6%。</p>上涨2.3%。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AIRYY" class="company-name">国航</a>股价上涨 4.5%。<p></p><p>日本政府发言人在周四的例行新闻发布会上赞扬了中国的举措。日本官员对今年旅游业的复苏表示欢迎，因为它带来了经济增长， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/japan-decides-tourism-pollution-is-worth-it-as-money-floods-in-f12b4053?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">尽管人们担心过度旅游</a>。</p><p>写信给 Selina Cheng，邮箱： <a href="mailto:selina.cheng@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">selina. Cheng@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-lifts-ban-on-group-tours-to-us-and-other-countries-in-boost-to-global-travel-industry-1b467c78</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-lifts-ban-on-group-tours-to-us-and-other-countries-in-boost-to-global-travel-industry-1b467c78<author><![CDATA[Selina Cheng]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>旅游</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category><category>旅游</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Colleges Spend Like There’s No Tomorrow. ‘These Places Are Just Devouring Money.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>学生们为旗舰州立大学买单，这些大学将资金投入到新建筑和项目中，几乎没有受到任何阻力<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833009/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108095"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108095"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/melissa-korn" itemprop="url" rel="author">Melissa Korn</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andrea-fuller" itemprop="url" rel="author">Andrea Fuller</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jennifer-s-forsyth" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jennifer S. Forsyth</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>美国最著名的公立大学一直在无限制地花钱。在过去的二十年里，他们建造了新的天际线，包括时髦的学术建筑和宿舍。他们向大型体育项目投入巨资，并聘请了多层管理人员。</p><p>然后他们将法案传递给学生。</p><p>肯塔基大学将其校园升级为十多年来每天花费 805,000 美元。其新生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/many-colleges-fail-in-push-to-boost-enrollment-of-lower-income-students-11663164001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来自美国最贫穷的州之一</a>，2021-22 学年的入学费用平均为 18,693 美元。</p><p>宾夕法尼亚州立大学花费了太多的钱，现在陷入了预算危机——尽管它是美国最昂贵的公立大学之一</p><p>俄克拉荷马大学的学费上涨幅度最大，同时斥资数百万美元用于项目，包括为其海外​​留学项目收购和翻修一座 32,000 平方英尺的意大利修道院。</p><p>这项支出与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nyu-college-graduate-parent-student-loans-11639618241?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国 1.6 万亿美元的联邦学生债务危机</a>有着千丝万缕的联系。大学通过提高学费来投入资金，这让许多学生别无选择，只能承担更多债务。这意味着学生贷款可以为大学项目提供轻松的融资。</p><p> “学生们现在没有资源来继续为大学想做的所有事情买单，”俄克拉荷马州 2023 届毕业生克里斯平·南 (Crispin South) 说。 “你不能仅仅通过向学生求助来继续增加收入。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1500" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/1980839d-de93-4796-9018-4224bb39ebf9-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>美国家庭长期以来都清楚，大学费用已经上涨，即使是那些旨在让州居民负担得起的公立学校也是如此。为了找出根本原因，《华尔街日报》检查了 2002 年以来 50 所旗舰大学（通常是各州最古老的公立学校）的财务报表，并根据通货膨胀进行了调整。</p><p> 2002 年至 2022 年间，中位旗舰大学的支出增长了 38%。</p><p>在《华尔街日报》的分析中，只有一所学校——爱达荷大学——的支出较少。</p><p>学校通过收取学费来支付部分费用。旗舰店的本科生和研究生学杂费收入中位数是 20 年前的两倍多。即使考虑到入学人数的增加，普通学生的物价上涨了 64%，远远超过了大多数家庭开支的增长。</p><h3>更多学费收入</h3><p>公立大学的领导者经常将提高学费收入的需要归咎于国家资金的吝啬。四分之三的州确实削减了支持，破坏了学校在政府支持下教育民众的长期原则。但大学普遍并没有因此勒紧裤腰带。相反，他们提高的价格远远超出了填补漏洞所需的水平。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》发现，过去 20 年来，这些大学的国家支持每损失 1 美元，中等学校的学杂费收入就会增加近 2.4 美元，超过了削减的金额。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1334" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5c3441d8-64ed-4f87-b10e-dbf69fcfa3da-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自始至终，学校都在一种重视持续增长、优先考虑增加收入而不是削减成本的文化中运作。管理人员制定了雄心勃勃的战略计划，并试图用豪华的设施来吸引富裕的学生。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-news-college-rankings-yale-law-fe24f0b2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">有影响力的大学排名奖励</a>那些花费更多的人。</p><p>许多大学官员很难了解自己的预算，只是每年都增加支出。受托人几乎不要求承担任何责任，而且常常对摆在他们面前的事情盖上橡皮图章。而且学校不一致地披露他们的支出情况，使得公众几乎不可能审查他们的学费和税款的使用方式。</p><p> “这些地方只是在吞噬金钱，”2008 年至 2013 年担任北卡罗来纳大学教堂山分校校长、现任《科学》杂志主编的霍顿·索普 (Holden Thorp) 说。他说，一次性向所有人提供一切是不可持续的。 “大学需要关注他们真正的优先事项是什么以及他们创建的目的是什么，”他说。</p><p>大学在课堂内外投入资金，包括改进技术、扩大咨询和校内体育活动，以及建设现代化宿舍和新体育场等设施。</p><p>为了检查公立大学的支出，《华尔街日报》从审计、存档预算网站以及通过公共记录请求收到的文件中收集了涵盖 2002 年、2012 年和 2022 年支出的数据。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》的分析发现，行政人员、教师、教练和财务专家的支出增长大部分体现在招聘过程中。工资和福利通常会占用运营预算的一半以上，但自 2002 年以来，中位旗舰店的工资和福利上涨了约 40%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829618?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上个月，肯塔基大学的学生中心。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829601?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">肯塔基州新电子竞技休息室中用于视频游戏的电脑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>2022年，佛罗里达大学拥有超过50名具有主任、副主任或传播助理主任职称的员工，大约是2017年人数的两倍。该校还聘用了超过160名助理、副院长、执行官和其他类型的院长去年，这一数字较 2017 年的约 130 有所增加。</p><p>发言人史蒂夫·奥兰多表示，该大学是权力下放的，不同部门可以根据需要自由招聘。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》对奈特-纽豪斯学院体育数据库数据的分析发现，2010 年至 2022 年间，旗舰学校经通胀调整后的体育教练支出增加了约一半。 《华尔街日报》使用了数据最完整时期的数据。</p><p>尽管少数实力雄厚的体育系可以自己支付费用， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/march-madness-is-a-moneymaker-most-schools-still-operate-in-red-11615545002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">但大多数只能靠学生学费和大学补贴才能收支平衡</a>。</p><p>在所有有可用数据的旗舰产品中，2022 年的额外资金总额为 6.32 亿美元。这比 12 年前增长了 27%。</p><p>康涅狄格大学今年春天赢得了男子篮球全国冠军，其女子篮球队几乎一直进入四强。然而，自 2016 年以来，康涅狄格州的体育系每年收到超过 3500 万美元的学生费用和大学补贴以维持生计。 2022 年，该基金获得了 5500 万美元的资金，占其体育总预算的一半以上。</p><p>学校表示，其中超过 1300 万美元的补贴用于支付一名前男子篮球教练，作为其雇佣合同法律和解的一部分，并且学校面临着必须支付租金和篮球和曲棍球比赛的其他费用的独特挑战。是在校外进行的。</p><p>总体而言，2002 年至 2022 年间，康涅狄格大学的支出增长了 73%，远远快于入学人数的增长。其中大部分是由人员成本推动的，福利支出增加了两倍多。</p><p>负责预算、规划和机构研究的副校长雷卡·乌林恩(Reka Wrynn)表示，部分原因是该校在该州无资金支持的养老金负债中所承担的责任越来越大。她说，康涅狄格州还有义务支付工会雇员与该州谈判的加薪费用。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829597?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">康涅狄格大学篮球队参加三月份的 NCAA 女子锦标赛。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：肖恩·埃利奥特/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>责任很少</h3><p>大学在预算方面几乎没有承担任何责任，部分原因是它们不需要以统一的方式跟踪费用。教育部关于大学财务的数据经常包含错误，并且与审计数据不符。</p><p>学校可以自行决定对经审计的财务报表上的支出进行分类，这使得对单个学校在一段时间内或不同学校之间进行精确比较非常困难。例如，大学有时将教授的工资分为一年的教学支出和下一年的研究费用。</p><p>田纳西大学诺克斯维尔分校研究大学财务的教育学教授罗伯特·凯尔琴（Robert Kelchen）表示，大学将审计“更多地视为一种要求，而不是公众的工具”。</p><p> 2002 年至 2012 年间，学校支出增长尤为强劲，总运营支出中位数增长了 30%。在经济衰退和大流行的双重财务压力下，一些学校在接下来的十年里开始缩减支出。在全国范围内对学生债务的强烈抗议中，他们还放慢了学费上涨的速度。</p><p>但支出仍在攀升。从 2012 年到 2022 年，中等大学的总运营费用增长了近 10%。</p><p>在某些情况下，随着学生人数的增长，大学的支出也会增加，典型的旗舰大学在过去二十年里招生人数增加了约 20%。在某些情况下，增加学生可能会很昂贵（需要新的宿舍和教室空间），或者相对便宜，尤其是对于在线学生而言。尽管如此，过去 20 年来，每个学生的支出中位数增加了 15%。</p><p>即使是美国最贫困州的学生，学校也将这笔费用转嫁给学生。大多数学校增加了对低收入学生的经济援助，但这并没有完全抵消许多家庭不断上涨的学费。</p><p>肯塔基州是全国家庭收入中位数最低的州之一。州内学生在 2021-22 年支付的费用使肯塔基州在按费用排名的旗舰学校中名列前茅。这些来自教育部的数据涵盖了新生在获得奖学金后平均支付的学费、杂费、食宿费用。</p><p>肯塔基州在其网站上宣称，在过去的十几年里，其列克星敦校区的翻修总共花费了 36.6 亿美元。其中包括法律、商业和视觉艺术学校的新校舍、最先进的医院设施、学生中心、拥有 900 个停车位的停车场、用于视频游戏比赛的剧院以及配有全尺寸 Tempur-Pedic 运动设施的宿舍床垫、花岗岩台面和内置洗衣干衣机。</p><p>私人开发商参与了一些项目，但总建筑成本的一半以上是由大学资金支付的。</p><p> “我们的宿舍满足学生和家庭的需求和期望，同时强调学习和联系，”大学发言人杰伊·布兰顿说。他说，宿舍的一些功能，例如工作台面，维护费用较低，而且购买 Tempur-Pedic 床垫的成本与传统床垫相当。</p><p>该校几十年前就立志成为全国最好的大学之一。具体来说，根据 1997 年的一项州政府指令，它的目标是跻身开展研究和提供博士学位的前 20 所公立学校之列。尽管有这项指令，立法机关还是开始减少资金。 20多年来，拨款减少了近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829623?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">肯塔基州学生中心的外观，近年来进行了升级和扩建。自2011年以来，学校斥资36.6亿美元改造校园。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829599?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">七月，肯塔基州校园正在施工。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·切里（Jon Cherry）为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“我们不会削减我们的愿望，”总统埃利·卡皮卢托 (Eli Capilouto) 2016 年表示。“但我们确实必须找到更有创意的方式来推动我们的进步。”肯塔基州增加了研究经费和教师工资，这有助于吸引人才。</p><p>一些大学排名，包括《美国新闻与世界报道》，奖励这些类别的支出以及俱乐部和文化活动等学生服务。他们不一定会赞扬那些让学校变得更有效率的举措。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/college-rankings-list-2022-11632246093?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《华尔街日报》的大学排名</a>也考虑了支出，但在即将发布的报告中将放弃这一衡量标准。</p><p>尽管肯塔基州做出了巨大的努力，《美国新闻与世界报道》将该校在 2022 年公立大学中排名第 64 位，实际上比十年前的排名下降了一些。</p><p>但学生的账单却增加了。肯塔基州每名学生的学杂费收入比 20 年前增加了约 70%。</p><p> 2017年，罗恩·里德（Rowan Reid）担任肯塔基州学生会主席，并在大学董事会中占有一席之地。当被要求投票支持将州内本科生的学费增加 4% 时，她敦促其他董事会成员让学校承担更多责任。</p><p>里德当时表示：“我们只将效率提高到可以将剩余赤字转嫁给学生的程度。” “对我来说，这感觉不对。”</p><p>学费上涨的比例为 16 比 1，里德是唯一投反对票的人。 Looking back this spring on her time with the board, Reid said she had a mandate to look out for students&#39; interests but was torn as to how she could reconcile that with what was best for the university.</p><p> The school said it has decelerated the rate of increase for tuition and fees over the past several years, and students from the lowest-income families receive scholarship support.</p><p> Blanton said Kentucky continues to grow and aspire to be recognized as one of the best public research institutions in the country but has shifted to a broader focus of advancing the state.</p><h3> Battle for the best students</h3><p> Schools loaded their campuses with state-of-the-art recreation centers and dorms to appeal to students with top test scores and minimal need for financial aid.这些设施的价格随后被纳入所有学生的账单中，包括学生支付的建筑债务费用。</p><p> Tuition and fee revenue per student climbed by double digits in the past 20 years at every school in the Journal&#39;s analysis. The average student paid more because many schools both upped prices and increased the percentage of higher-paying students from out of state. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="3268" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/4e1b3086-4f54-4f8b-ad64-239b2396927d-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> At the University of Oklahoma, per-student tuition and fees rose 166%, the most of any flagship.学校还借了数亿美元进行建筑升级和建造新宿舍。</p><p> “We levered up the balance sheet to avoid dealing with [financial] reality,” said Oklahoma President Joseph Harroz Jr. , who took the helm in 2019. Across higher education, he said, “there was an arms race.”</p><p> Beginning in 2009, the university spent $14.3 million to buy and renovate a monastery in Arezzo, Italy, to house a new study-abroad program. The monastery has a landscaped garden, faculty apartment and classrooms featuring painted frescoes.</p><p> The school said it was paid for by a mix of private gifts and university funds.</p><p> “Would I go and do one of those right now?不，”哈罗斯说。 “It wouldn&#39;t be the best use of capital dollars.”</p><p> Harroz said that under some of his predecessors, the school didn&#39;t maintain long-term budget plans or prioritize its needs over its wishes. Oklahoma has since changed course, he said, and the university cut $143 million in expenses at the main campus in Norman since 2018.</p><p> The increase in tuition at Oklahoma came after the state legislature gave school regents tuition-setting authority in the early 2000s, a move designed to allow the school to catch up with its peers&#39; rates, said University of Oklahoma spokeswoman April Sandefer. She said its increases have slowed in recent years, and more than half of Oklahoma undergraduates leave school debt-free thanks to a growing financial-aid budget.</p><h3> License to spend</h3><p> Research by James V. Koch, an economist who studies college spending and a former president at Old Dominion University in Virginia, found that public-university trustees approved 98% of the cost-increasing proposals they reviewed, often unanimously. In most states, he said, there hasn&#39;t been anyone to say, “No, you can&#39;t do that.”</p><p> Back in 2005, a Hawaii state audit called out the University of Hawaii System board for approving a budget that gave the flagship Manoa campus $200 million when, auditors said, all but $13 million went to vague or unnecessary requests.</p><p> Honolulu attorney Benjamin Kudo, who joined the university&#39;s board in 2011, said he was stunned by the lack of information he was given during the budget process.他说，他收到了一包饼图和一份 PowerPoint 演示文稿，其中包含有关该大学计划如何在 10 个校区的教学、图书馆、体育和设施等领域分配资金的一般信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829600?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The University of Oklahoma&#39;s campus in Arezzo, Italy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The University of Oklahoma </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829596?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Norman campus at Oklahoma. The school borrowed hundreds of millions of dollars to perform building upgrades and erect new dormitories.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kudo said administrators weren&#39;t initially receptive to requests that he and another new board member, Jan Sullivan, made for more detail, including a comparison of projected versus actual spending.工藤在董事会任职至 2022 年，他回忆起自己曾被指责试图对 10 亿美元的预算进行微观管理。</p><p> School officials expected him to follow the lead of prior trustees, Kudo said: “It&#39;s basically an automatic approval of whatever the administration wants.”</p><p> Sullivan also said such rubber stamping was typical early in her tenure.沙利文和工藤说，经过几年的唠叨，董事会收到了更详细的财务信息，并停止批准这么多请求。</p><p> University of Hawaii President David Lassner said the university has changed.大约十年前，在他被任命为临时总裁后不久，董事会通过审查财政年度结束六个月后发布的经审计的财务报表，发现储备金已耗尽，他对此进行了谴责。</p><p> “That is no way to understand the financial health of something as big and complicated as this,” he said. “We&#39;re certainly not budgeting by pie charts anymore.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="464" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831288?width=700&amp;height=464" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> University of Hawaii President David Lassner, center, at the ceremony to officially name him president of the school in 2014.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: University of Hawaii</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> &#39;Knee-jerk reaction&#39;</h3><p> Penn State, like many schools, long relied on a simple approach to budgeting, in which each department generally received the same amount of money it got the prior year plus a little more to cover inflation. Dollars were rarely tied to enrollment shifts or demonstrated need.</p><p> The school&#39;s spending rose 36% since 2002. That number excludes the university&#39;s health system, which the Journal removed from its analysis where possible. Total tuition and fee revenue from both undergraduate and graduate students increased 72% over the past two decades, far faster than enrollment grew.</p><p> Penn State&#39;s University Park campus was the country&#39;s most expensive state flagship in the 2021-22 school year for in-state freshmen after scholarships.根据教育部的数据，这些学生平均支付 26,747 美元的学费、杂费、食宿费用。</p><p> The school said it offers students the option of starting at one of its less expensive regional campuses and finishing at University Park, and has increased financial aid significantly. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1594" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/2b99b9f0-3109-4607-9038-fffbc5ecc301-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Penn State cut spending nearly 3% between 2012 and 2022. Still, the university&#39;s 2022-23 budget forecast spending that was $140 million more than its revenue.</p><p> It&#39;s not the first time expenditures were projected to outpace revenue, and Penn State determined last year it was on track to blow through its $350 million reserve funds in the next few years if it didn&#39;t change course. Trustees gave the administration until 2025 to balance the budget.</p><p> Trustee Barry Fenchak criticized his fellow board members at the meeting when they voted last summer to increase tuition and fees by 5% for in-state students at the University Park campus after the state held funding flat.</p><p> “I think the knee-jerk reaction was, &#39;OK, we&#39;ve got to raise tuition,&#39; and I think perhaps the knee-jerk reaction should have been, &#39;We need to get to work on the things we should&#39;ve been doing for the last 10 years and light a bit of a fire underneath our behinds&#39; ” to address costs, he said.</p><p> Several trustees at the meeting said the decision was based on thorough analysis.</p><p> At meeting after meeting for decades, Penn State board members complained of the state&#39;s anemic support while they simultaneously approved hundreds of millions of dollars in new construction, according to board minutes.</p><p> The university&#39;s state appropriation fell 39% over the past 20 years, and the school receives among the lowest state support per student of US flagships. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831761?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Penn State&#39;s University Park campus in April. The school spent so much money that it now has a budget crisis, even though it&#39;s among the most expensive public universities in the US</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: aul Weaver/Sipa/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Growth in tuition revenue has more than made up for declining state funding. On a per-student basis, Penn State received nearly $2.25 in additional tuition revenue for every $1 lost in state support, compared with $1.25 in tuition revenue added at the median school.</p><p> “We acknowledge that tuition has increased quite a bit over the past 20 years, which is a large stretch of time for such a comparison when taking into account growth in student needs, services, technology, stem fields, academic support, mental health services etc. and considering our stagnant state funding,” said Lisa Powers, a school spokeswoman.</p><p> Mary Isaacson, a Democrat and chair of the subcommittee on higher education in the Pennsylvania House of Representatives, said that while public funding declined, the school&#39;s aggressive physical growth and lengthy wish list also helped put it on its path to financial insecurity.</p><p> Penn State said much of the construction was necessary to replace aging facilities, and that factors such as inflation and the pandemic drove up costs, too.</p><p> The university said last year it would revise the way it sets its operating budget. The new model, it said, will take into account enrollment changes and available resources, and be data-driven.</p><p> Write to Melissa Korn at <a href="mailto:Melissa.Korn@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Melissa.Korn@wsj.com</a> , Andrea Fuller at <a href="mailto:andrea.fuller@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrea.fuller@wsj.com</a> and Jennifer S. Forsyth at <a href="mailto:Jennifer.Forsyth@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jennifer.Forsyth@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>方法</h4><p>To examine colleges&#39; spending patterns, the Journal supplemented figures from audited financial statements from 2002, 2012 and 2022 with data from public information requests and other documents. All numbers in the analysis were adjusted to 2022 dollars. Figures representing the median flagship were calculated by taking the median of the change at each school.</p><p> Some schools said they didn&#39;t keep historical records of every figure the Journal sought, such as salary and benefits spending. The Journal asked colleges to provide information for only the main flagship campus, but not all schools said they were able to do so. The figures for roughly one third of the universities in the Journal&#39;s analysis include data for some branch campuses, with data for several states representing large university systems.</p><p> The Journal asked colleges to exclude health systems and hospital operations from the figures, but not all did so. Health-related expenses can make up a large share of operating budgets, and universities that included hospitals in their figures tended to have among the largest increases in total operating expenses. However, the overall median increase in operating expenses was roughly similar whether or not the Journal included these schools in its analysis.</p><p> Separately, the Journal used data from the Education Department that covered the price in-state students typically paid. These figures, known as net price, cover the average cost of first-time, full-time students who received scholarships.</p><p> Per-student tuition revenue figures, derived from data in audited financial statements, reflect money paid by all students, including graduate and out-of-state. As a result, these calculations don&#39;t match the net-price figures.</p><p> Enrollment figures, also from the Education Department, reflect what is known as full-time equivalent enrollment. To calculate this, the Journal used a formula similar to the Education Department&#39;s method, taking into account the mix of full- and part-time undergraduate and graduate students each fall.</p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100<author><![CDATA[Melissa KornAndrea FullerJennifer S. Forsyth]]></author><category> wsjinvestigations</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>领导者</category><category>photo-commission</category><category>教育</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学学院</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Career Education</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>career education </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Yo Jong: What We Know About Kim Jong Un’s Sister and Her Role in North Korea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The dictator&#39;s sister has star power, a rising political profile and is called the country&#39;s de facto No. 2 leader <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11793591577686923893604587148733765658576"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-270505?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Kim Yo Jong, pictured in 2018, has risen in prominence as confidante and adviser to her brother Kim Jong Un, the North Korean leader.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ryu Seung-Il/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11793591577686923893604587148733765658576"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">蒂莫西·W·马丁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 10, 2023 3:27 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-sister-kim-yo-jong-11607524273"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Kim Yo Jong, believed to be at least 34 years old, is a senior North Korean official helping oversee the country&#39;s policies toward the US and South Korea, according to Seoul&#39;s intelligence agency, which has referred to her as the country&#39;s de facto No. 2 leader.</p><p> Among her various titles, Kim is the nominal head of the North&#39;s propaganda and agitation department. She rose to prominence in just the past several years, attending all three face-to-face meetings between then-President Donald Trump and North Korean leader <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">Kim Jong Un</a> , as the latter&#39;s confidante and adviser. In September 2021, she was promoted to the State Affairs Commission, the North&#39;s top decision-making body. More recently, she <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-accuses-u-s-spy-plane-of-territorial-intrusion-422bafa3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">issues state-media attacks</a> against the US, South Korea and others <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-yo-jong-blasts-skeptics-of-north-koreas-military-advances-11671526251?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">who doubt the Kim regime</a> .</p><h3> Who is Kim Yo Jong and what do we know about her?</h3><p> Kim Yo Jong&#39;s precise date of birth is unknown, though South Korea&#39;s Unification Ministry database of North Korean officials lists her as being born in 1988 in Pyongyang. She is the younger sister of Kim Jong Un and the youngest-known daughter of their father Kim Jong Il, who ruled North Korea from 1994 to 2011 and had children with several women. During her earliest years, Ms. Kim was an obscure figure. That changed in 2009, when Kim Jong Un was rumored to have been named heir to the North Korean leadership, after their father <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204791104577107922829964182?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">suffered a series of strokes</a> . That year, a side-by-side photograph was shown on state media, showing a presumed image of her, alongside Kim Jong Un and their eldest full brother, Kim Jong Chol. News cameras also spotted her in early 2011, when <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-KRTB-1655?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">she attended an Eric Clapton concert</a> in Singapore with Jong Chol.</p><p> Her marital status is unknown, though some South Korean news outlets have mentioned she may have married the son of a prominent North Korean official, Choe Ryong Hae, Kim Jong Un&#39;s deputy in the state affairs commission—the government&#39;s most-powerful decision-making apparatus. She hasn&#39;t been publicly seen with a husband in North Korean state media. Kim steadily gained international prominence as Kim Jong Un <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-is-accelerating-plan-to-land-missiles-in-u-s-1494792608?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">accelerated North Korea&#39;s nuclear weapons development</a> over the past decade, participating in nuclear negotiations involving the US and South Korea since 2018. In 2020, when her brother <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-kim-jong-un-disappears-north-korea-watchers-advise-caution-11587918517?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was rumored to be seriously ill</a> , North Korea experts mentioned her as a possible emergency backup, if her brother abruptly died, or was incapacitated.</p><p> She boasts a key requirement to become the North&#39;s Supreme Leader: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-would-succeed-kim-jong-un-in-north-korea-look-to-mount-paektu-11588179168?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">she hails from the “Mount Paektu bloodline,”</a> or those with a direct lineage to the country&#39;s founder Kim Il Sung. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-270502?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The two siblings met with South Korean President Moon Jae-in inside the demilitarized zone separating the two Koreas in 2018.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Korea Summit Press Pool</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> What is her political role in North Korea?</h3><p> Ms. Kim has held an official post in the North Korean government since at least 2014, according to the Seoul government, serving in the country&#39;s rubber-stamp parliament. She also serves in the Central Committee of the ruling Workers&#39; Party, the party&#39;s executive body. In 2018, she received international attention when <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korean-president-to-meet-kim-jong-uns-sister-1518081856?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">she traveled to South Korea</a> as her brother&#39;s emissary, to discuss how North Korea could participate in that year&#39;s Winter Olympics, which was hosted in Pyeongchang, South Korea. She later <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amid-tense-geopolitical-backdrop-pyeongchang-opening-ceremony-stresses-harmony-1518176121?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">appeared at the Games&#39; opening ceremony</a> seated near then-Vice President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">Mike Pence</a> . She became the first known member of North Korea&#39;s ruling Kim family to visit the South.</p><p> Ms. Kim then <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-heralds-very-comprehensive-agreement-with-kim-jong-un-1528783602?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">traveled to Singapore</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-north-koreas-kim-end-nuclear-summit-early-11551334804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Vietnam and the inter-Korean border</a> to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-says-north-koreas-kim-wants-to-meet-11561862697?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">attend unprecedented</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-says-north-koreas-kim-wants-to-meet-11561862697?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">face-to-face meetings</a> between her brother and Mr. Trump, as a confidante and adviser to her brother.</p><p> In March 2020, a North Korean government statement under her name was released for the first time. That statement rebuked South Korea for criticizing a recent military exercise conducted by the Kim regime days before. She has since become the North&#39;s go-to figure to talk publicly about US and South Korean affairs.</p><p> Since then, Kim Yo Jong has warned the Biden administration of “causing a stink,” protested combined Washington-Seoul military exercises and ridiculed South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol&#39;s attempts at rapprochement.</p><h3> Is she next in line to succeed Kim Jong Un?</h3><p> There are no publicly known rules that precisely outline North Korea&#39;s leadership succession. But in the two successions that have occurred in the country since its founding in 1948, the incumbent leader has handpicked and groomed an adult son to succeed him upon his death. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> A Family Affair</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-would-succeed-kim-jong-un-in-north-korea-look-to-mount-paektu-11588179168?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Who Would Succeed Kim Jong Un in North Korea? Look to Mount Paektu</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korean-president-to-meet-kim-jong-uns-sister-1518081856?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Kim Jong Un&#39;s Sister, South Korea&#39;s Leader to Do Lunch</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-will-send-his-sister-to-the-winter-olympics-1517990328?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Kim Jong Un&#39;s Sister to Attend Olympics</a></li></ul></div></div><p> Kim could be a temporary regent who would inherit North Korea&#39;s leadership, should the incumbent Kim Jong Un abruptly die, or fall seriously ill, according to longtime North Korea watchers. In April 2020, amid widespread speculation that her brother could be incapacitated or dead, Kim Yo Jong was seen as a potential backup. That was due to her blood ties to the ruling Kim family, the fact that all of Kim Jong Un&#39;s children were under 18, and because other male members of the Kim family were seen as politically sidelined. In August that year, Seoul&#39;s intelligence agency said Ms. Kim was Pyongyang&#39;s de facto No. 2, though she may not be an officially designated heir.</p><h3> What is her relationship with Kim Jong Un?</h3><p> Kim Yo Jong is likely the only adviser that Kim Jong Un trusts, North Korea experts say, due to their shared blood and her unimposing presence.</p><p> Kim has often appeared to help her brother stand out, instead of competing for power or public attention. She is portrayed in North Korean state media as accompanying her brother during official visits to the country&#39;s factories, farmlands, and government offices in a deputy role, quietly offering advice and assistance, and with a notebook in hand. Her younger age is also seen as an asset in winning the North Korean leader&#39;s confidence, North Korea experts say, as age is a determining factor in seniority in Korean culture.</p><p> Kim was rumored to have been demoted after the Hanoi summit in February 2019 failed to produce a denuclearization deal. But she was reinstated to the country&#39;s Politburo and attended many of her brother&#39;s showcase events—including in May 2020 when <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-is-said-to-have-attended-factory-opening-11588374281?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Kim Jong Un reappeared at a factory opening</a> after the world speculated he might be dead.</p><p> In November 2022, Kim was shown crying in celebration of the country&#39;s Hwasong-17 intercontinental ballistic missile launch, a marquee North Korean event. Kim Jong Un was photographed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-koreas-kim-jong-un-puts-daughter-on-view-at-icbm-launch-11668844562?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">holding hands with his daughter</a> —and Kim&#39;s niece—in what was the first public appearance from one of the North Korean leader&#39;s children.</p><p> Her relationship with her elder brother is compared with that between their father Kim Jong Il, and his younger sister, Kim Kyong Hui, who was the North Korean ruler&#39;s sole surviving full sibling. Those two shared a tragic past: their mother died during childbirth when both were children, while another brother died in a drowning accident a year earlier. Kim Kyong Hui had helped her brother&#39;s rule by overseeing parts of the country&#39;s communist economy and serving as an adviser. But as aunt to Kim Jong Un after he rose to power, her public life had remained sidelined, while her husband, Jang Song Thaek, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303932504579254632008825604?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was purged and believed executed</a> in 2013. Kim Kyong Hui <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304403804579259603815824842?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was photographed as recently as January</a> 2020, attending a concert in Pyongyang with Kim Jong Un. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-270524?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Kim serves in the Central Committee of the Workers&#39; Party.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Press Pool</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> How is Kim Yo Jong perceived by North Koreans?</h3><p> It is impossible to accurately gauge her standing among the overall North Korean public, due to the authoritarian government&#39;s ability to execute citizens who even slightly criticize the Kim regime. But the public is likely to be unaccustomed to having a young woman in a senior government position, as the great majority of those in such roles in North Korea have been older males. Her relationship with her brother Kim Jong Un, though, means she can demand respect—real or feigned—from the North Korean elite, who mostly live in the capital city of Pyongyang. In 2018, an 89-year-old Kim Yong Nam —North Korea&#39;s then-nominal head of state, as the chief of the country&#39;s rubber-stamp legislature—bowed in deference to Kim when the two <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-will-send-his-sister-to-the-winter-olympics-1517990328?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">led a North Korean delegation to South Korea</a> , in front of South Korean news cameras.</p><h3> How is she perceived abroad?</h3><p> She has been seen as an influential North Korean aide to the country&#39;s leader due to her relationship with Kim Jong Un and participation in major diplomatic meetings with the US, China and South Korea. Her harsh rhetoric directed toward senior South Korean officials in 2020—including President Moon Jae -in—was seen as unusual by Seoul officials, as they had <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-south-korea-meeting-to-determine-their-future-ties-1524749462?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shared private conversations and drinks</a> with Kim in recent inter-Korean meetings. Most remembered her as soft-spoken and polite.</p><p> In the US, she was sometimes perceived to be an unofficial counterpart to Ivanka Trump, who had served as an adviser to her father and accompanied him on diplomatic engagements with North Korea. The two also crossed paths in the 2018 Winter Olympics. Kim attended the opening ceremony as the unofficial head of the North Korean delegation, while <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/winter-olympics-wind-down-with-plenty-of-razzle-dazzle-1519566208?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Trump attended the closing ceremony</a> as the leader of the US delegation.</p><p> Kim has also been seen as a complicit violator of human rights by human rights organizations and the US government. Her senior role in North Korea makes her partly responsible for the Kim regime&#39;s continued executions, incarcerations and oppression of political prisoners, they say. Her role in a government propaganda department also links her to the Kim regime&#39;s censorship activities, the Treasury Department said in January 2017, when <a href="https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl0699.aspx" target="_blank" class="icon none">it added her to its sanctions list</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
